## Binding and mutability
1. ğŸŒŸ A variable can be used only if it has been initialized.
```rust,editable

// Fix the error below with least amount of modification to the code
fn main() {
    let x: i32; // Uninitialized but used, ERROR !
    let y: i32; // Uninitialized but also unused, only a Warning !

    assert_eq!(x, 5);
    println!("Success!");
}
```
fn main() {
    let x: i32 = 5; // Ğ†Ğ½Ñ–Ñ†Ñ–Ğ°Ğ»Ñ–Ğ·ÑƒÑ”Ğ¼Ğ¾ x Ğ·Ğ½Ğ°Ñ‡ĞµĞ½Ğ½ÑĞ¼ 5
    let y: i32;      // ĞœĞ¾Ğ¶Ğ½Ğ° Ğ·Ğ°Ğ»Ğ¸ÑˆĞ¸Ñ‚Ğ¸, Ğ±Ğ¾ Ñ†Ğµ Ğ»Ğ¸ÑˆĞµ Ğ¿Ğ¾Ğ¿ĞµÑ€ĞµĞ´Ğ¶ĞµĞ½Ğ½Ñ

    assert_eq!(x, 5);
    println!("Success!");
}

2. ğŸŒŸ Use `mut` to mark a variable as mutable.
```rust,editable

// Fill the blanks in the code to make it compile
fn main() {
    let __ __ = 1;
    __ += 2; 
    
    assert_eq!(x, 3);
    println!("Success!");
}
```
fn main() {
    let mut x = 1; // Ğ·Ğ¼Ñ–Ğ½Ğ½Ğ° mutable Ñ– Ğ½Ğ°Ğ·Ğ¸Ğ²Ğ°Ñ”Ñ‚ÑŒÑÑ x
    x += 2;        // Ğ´Ğ¾Ğ´Ğ°Ñ”Ğ¼Ğ¾ 2
    
    assert_eq!(x, 3);
    println!("Success!");
}

### Scope
A scope is the range within the program for which the item is valid.

3. ğŸŒŸ 
```rust,editable

// Fix the error below with least amount of modification
fn main() {
    let x: i32 = 10;
    {
        let y: i32 = 5;
        println!("Inner scope value of x is {} and value of y is {}", x, y);
    }
    println!("Outer scope value of x is {} and value of y is {}", x, y); 
}
```
fn main() {
    let x: i32 = 10;
    let y: i32; // Ğ¾Ğ³Ğ¾Ğ»Ğ¾ÑĞ¸Ğ»Ğ¸ y Ğ·Ğ¾Ğ²Ğ½Ñ–

    {
        y = 5; // Ñ–Ğ½Ñ–Ñ†Ñ–Ğ°Ğ»Ñ–Ğ·ÑƒÑ”Ğ¼Ğ¾ y Ğ²ÑĞµÑ€ĞµĞ´Ğ¸Ğ½Ñ– Ğ²Ğ½ÑƒÑ‚Ñ€Ñ–ÑˆĞ½ÑŒĞ¾Ğ³Ğ¾ Ğ±Ğ»Ğ¾ĞºÑƒ
        println!("Inner scope value of x is {} and value of y is {}", x, y);
    }

    println!("Outer scope value of x is {} and value of y is {}", x, y); 
}

4. ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ 
```rust,editable

// Fix the error with the use of define_x
fn main() {
    println!("{}, world", x); 
}

fn define_x() {
    let x = "hello";
}
```
fn main() {
    let x = define_x();           // Ğ·Ğ±ĞµÑ€Ñ–Ğ³Ğ°Ñ”Ğ¼Ğ¾ Ñ€ĞµĞ·ÑƒĞ»ÑŒÑ‚Ğ°Ñ‚ Ñƒ x
    println!("{}, world", x); 
}

fn define_x() -> &'static str {   // Ñ„ÑƒĞ½ĞºÑ†Ñ–Ñ Ğ¿Ğ¾Ğ²ĞµÑ€Ñ‚Ğ°Ñ” Ñ€ÑĞ´Ğ¾Ğº
    "hello"                        // Ğ¿Ğ¾Ğ²ĞµÑ€Ñ‚Ğ°Ñ”Ğ¼Ğ¾ "hello"
}

### Shadowing
You can declare a new variable with the same name as a previous variable, here we can say **the first one is shadowed by the second one.**

5. ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ 
```rust,editable

// Only modify `assert_eq!` to make the `println!` work(print `42` in terminal)
fn main() {
    let x: i32 = 5;
    {
        let x = 12;
        assert_eq!(x, 5);
    }

    assert_eq!(x, 12);

    let x = 42;
    println!("{}", x); // Prints "42".
}
```
fn main() {
    let x: i32 = 5;
    {
        let x = 12;
        assert_eq!(x, 12); // Ğ·Ğ¼Ñ–Ğ½Ğ¸Ğ»Ğ¸ Ğ½Ğ° 12
    }

    assert_eq!(x, 5);      // Ğ·Ğ¼Ñ–Ğ½Ğ¸Ğ»Ğ¸ Ğ½Ğ° 5

    let x = 42;
    println!("{}", x); // Prints "42".
}

6. ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ 
```rust,editable

// fn main() {
    let mut x: i32 = 1;
    x = 7;
    // Shadowing and re-binding
    let x = x; 
    x += 3;


    let y = 4;
    // Shadowing
    let y = "I can also be bound to text!"; 

    println!("Success!");
}

fn main() {
    let mut x: i32 = 1;
    x = 7;
    // Shadowing and re-binding
    // let x = x;  <- Ğ²Ğ¸Ğ´Ğ°Ğ»Ğ¸Ğ»Ğ¸
    x += 3;


    let y = 4;
    // Shadowing
    let y = "I can also be bound to text!"; 

    println!("Success!");
}

### Unused variables
7. Fix the warning below with :

- ğŸŒŸ  Only one solution
- ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ  Two distinct solutions

> Note: none of the solutions is to remove the line `let x = 1` 

```rust,editable

fn main() {
    let x = 1; 
}

// Warning: unused variable: `x`
```
fn main() {
    let x = 1;
    println!("{}", x); // Ğ²Ğ¸ĞºĞ¾Ñ€Ğ¸ÑÑ‚Ğ°Ğ»Ğ¸ x â†’ warning Ğ·Ğ½Ğ¸ĞºĞ°Ñ”
}

fn main() {
    let _x = 1; // ĞºĞ¾Ğ¼Ğ¿Ñ–Ğ»ÑÑ‚Ğ¾Ñ€ Ñ–Ğ³Ğ½Ğ¾Ñ€ÑƒÑ” Ğ½ĞµĞ²Ğ¸ĞºĞ¾Ñ€Ğ¸ÑÑ‚Ğ°Ğ½Ğ½Ñ
}

### Destructuring
8. ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ We can use a pattern with `let` to destructure a tuple to separate variables.

> Tips: you can use Shadowing or Mutability

```rust,editable

// Fix the error below with least amount of modification
fn main() {
    let (x, y) = (1, 2);
    x += 2;

    assert_eq!(x, 3);
    assert_eq!(y, 2);

    println!("Success!");
}
```

### Destructuring assignments
Introduced in Rust 1.59: You can now use tuple, slice, and struct patterns as the left-hand side of an assignment.

fn main() {
    let (x, y) = (1, 2);
    let x = x + 2; // ğŸŒŸ shadowing, ÑÑ‚Ğ²Ğ¾Ñ€ÑÑ”Ğ¼Ğ¾ Ğ½Ğ¾Ğ²Ğ¸Ğ¹ x
     
    assert_eq!(x, 3);
    assert_eq!(y, 2);

    println!("Success!");
}

fn main() {
    let (mut x, y) = (1, 2); // ğŸŒŸ x mutable
    x += 2;

    assert_eq!(x, 3);
    assert_eq!(y, 2);

    println!("Success!");
}

9. ğŸŒŸğŸŒŸ

> Note: the feature `Destructuring assignments` need 1.59 or higher Rust version

```rust,editable

fn main() {
    let (x, y);
    (x,..) = (3, 4);
    [.., y] = [1, 2];
    // Fill the blank to make the code work
    assert_eq!([x,y], __);

    println!("Success!");
} 
```
fn main() {
    let (x, y);
    (x,..) = (3, 4);
    [.., y] = [1, 2];

    assert_eq!([x, y], [3, 2]); // âœ… Ğ·Ğ°Ğ¿Ğ¾Ğ²Ğ½Ğ¸Ğ»Ğ¸ blank

    println!("Success!");
}

